<br>
Good, thorough post. I'm more than willing to help anyone else in the guild on their epics. But since you sort of invited my opinion in with your post...<br>
<br>
I don't want to come from the perspective of an individual saying &quot;help me, only my epic is important.&quot; I'm actually saying this as I've been on the flip side of the coin - how do you, as a raid leader, know who is where on their epic? And how, as an individual, do you get everyone to come along and help you?<br>
<br>
I'm not sure as I've only been here three days, but I assume that despite not having titles, there are a few people whom everyone turns to to lead the raids. Now, as this leader, if you don't know what stage everyone is at you can't schedule a fair raiding schedule. <br>
<br>
It's all fine and good to do raids for friends as they send you tells, but maybe some people are less outgoing then say - me.<br>
<br>
I note that Twig started a string for epics - it would be cool if something like that could be stickied in one spot and as epic stages were accomplished topics could be deleted. I really don't know how to exactly set it up as I know epics can sometimes be a sensitive issue for everyone.<br>
<br>
How do you keep things fair? How do you keep from stepping on someone's toes as a raid leader when you say &quot;I'm sorry so and so asked me to do theirs first - I promis you're next.&quot; Invariably someone's toes are going to get stepped on unless the rules are pretty straight.<br>
<br>
Anyways, I hope I'm not giving the impression that I'm trying to impose or manipulate as that is not my intention. When I join a guild I put 100% effort into supporting it. I only left BWH after having spent over a year with them because it essentially folded during my leave of absence. I joined Amazon because I like the kind of laid back, family atmosphere, with raids mixed in - you guys have done a great job here in that regards. <br>
<br>
